  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Family Reunification and Re-integreation of Streetchildren in Kinshasa (DRC)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">20,000 girls and boys, many accused of being witches, are living on the streets of the Democratic Republic of Congo. Every day they face the risk of abuse, drug-addiction and violence. This project helps find street children and encourages them to visit a drop-in centre. Here staff offer medical care, a meal, washing facilities, games and classes to teach them to read and write. There is a temporary shelter for girls. It helps the children go back to school or train to get a job. The project finds their families and helps them with their problems so the children can return home. Staff visit families regularly, offering them small loans to start small businesses and help with their rent. The project broadcasts radio programmes and organises meetings with local church leaders, government authorities and the community, to tackle people&#x2019;s attitudes towards the children, especially the belief in child witchcraft.</narrative>
  </description>
